</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
468 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
NONFICTION IN BRIEF: FALL FROM GRACE: THE FAILED CRUSADE OF THE CHRISTIAN RIGHT 
BY MICHAEL D'ANTONIO (FARRAR, STRAUS &amp; GIROUX: $19.95; 242 PP.) 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SONJA BOLLE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
This account by former Newsday religion writer Michael D'Antonio of the 
Christian Right's brief bid for political power in the figure of Pat Robertson 
is worth perusing for the rapid Chapter 1 overview alone, in which the writer's 
trenchant style makes short work of the absurdities in the movement. 
</P>
<P>
But that is an easy target. The main body of the book contains case histories 
of born-again Christians and scenes from D'Antonio's travels around the country 
to various born-again and charismatic congregations. The stories here are 
wonderfully revealing, even if D'Antonio's comments are equally revealing of 
his disdain for the sort of people who fall for Jesus talk. He visits Jimmy and 
Tammy Bakker's Heritage USA as well as Oral Roberts' City of Faith (where he is 
told that security guards will identify him because he sports that common 
journalist's eccentricity: a beard). As he looks at the reasons for people's 
conversions, D'Antonio lays bare the curious connection between the born-again 
Christian life and American conservative political ideas. A chapter on the 
pageant celebrating the bicentennial of the Constitution at the massive Second 
Baptist Church of Houston explores the peculiar rewriting of history for 
emotional effect that dovetailed beautifully, D'Antonio maintains, with the 
Republican strategy in the 1980 and 1984 presidential campaigns. 
</P>
<P>
The collapse of the religious right as a political force, D'Antonio says, was 
"eerily familiar from such works of fiction as 'Elmer Gantry' . . . Big-time, 
moralizing evangelists had always been undone by the sin of greed and the sins 
of the flesh." The spectacular fall and media feeding frenzy that followed the 
televangelist scandals finally allowed the Republicans to criticize the 
Christian groups without fear of being labeled suppressors of religion. When 
the Bush campaign attacked, D'Antonio says, "it became clear that the Christian 
Right was less a juggernaut than a man of straw." 
</P>
<P>
D'Antonio portrays the turn to the right as a logical but short-lived backlash 
against the gains made by the civil-rights and women's movements, which he 
unequivocally describes as "inevitable." His account leaves open no doubt that 
the Christian Right has evaporated as a political force. This is a comforting 
thought if one is not suspicious enough to look with a watchful eye at events 
outside of American borders. Religious fundamentalism may not have won the 
Republican presidential nomination in 1988, and the televangelists' empires may 
indeed have crumbled beyond repair, but it still seems overly optimistic to 
say, as D'Antonio does, that "Bush's election ensured the death of a movement, 
as he returned the nation to the professional politics of Nixon and Ford and 
abandoned the anomalous populism of Reagan and Falwell." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Book Review; Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
