<P>
Photo, World War II GIs gather for a song around a Steinway "Victory Vertical" 
piano sent out by the company to entertain the troops. During the war, the New 
York Steinway factory was barred from making pianos, as they used materials 
required for the military effort; the shop was modified to make parts for troop 
transport gliders instead. The richly illustrated "Steinway" by Ronald V. 
Ratcliffe (Chronicle Books: $40) recounts the history of the American 
piano-making family and the 125-year-old firm that has manufactured pianos for 
some of the world's most famous musicians. 
</P>
