<HEADLINE>
<P>
AGAINST 'B-1 BOB,' FORGET THE DIGNITY; 
</P>
<P>
POLITICS: VETERAN RON KOVIC ASKS FOR A 'CAMPAIGN OF STATESMANSHIP' IF HE RUNS 
AGAINST REP. ROBERT DORNAN IN ORANGE COUNTY. HE WILL HAVE TO SETTLE FOR 
BRICKBATS. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Christopher Matthews, Christopher Matthews writes a syndicated column in 
Washington. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Ron Kovic, the paralyzed war hero of "Born on the Fourth of July," is readying 
for a new firefight. This time, the terrain will not be the jungles of Vietnam 
but the John Wayne politics of Orange County. This time, his rival will not be 
the Viet Cong but Robert "B-1 Bob" Dornan, the most hawkish member of the U.S. 
Congress. 
</P>
<P>
While the 44-year-old combat veteran has yet to formally declare a challenge to 
the reelection of the archconservative Dornan, shrapnel has begun to fly. 
</P>
<P>
Kovic, an out-and-out critic of U.S. policy in Vietnam, says he is "deeply 
concerned" by the President's decision to invade Panama. "Are we going into 
Nicaragua next? Into El Salvador?" He attacks what he calls the "wall of fear" 
put up by the Administration and Dornan toward other countries in this 
hemisphere. 
</P>
<P>
"It takes more courage to make friends than it does to pull a trigger," he 
says. "As a congressman, I would build bridges of friendship with our neighbors 
instead of this policy of fear and hostility." 
</P>
<P>
Kovic hopes that his campaign for Congress will "remind people about what 
really happened in Vietnam so it won't happen again." Admitting that he is not 
a "professional" in the political world, he hopes his challenge to Dornan will 
be a "campaign of statesmanship," conducted on a "high plane of dignity." 
</P>
<P>
Not likely. If Kovic wanted a high-toned debate over America's proper role in 
the world, he picked the wrong opponent. 
</P>
<P>
Bob Dornan, the man whose congressional seat Kovic has targeted, despises such 
second-guessing of American policy. He has particular disdain for those like 
Kovic and filmmaker Oliver Stone who portray Americans as "scum" in the world's 
eyes. 
</P>
<P>
"If (Kovic) hadn't been shot," says the man with a 100% conservative, 
pro-military voting record, "he'd have been strutting about his two tours in 
Vietnam." 
</P>
<P>
It gets worse. The 56-year-old Dornan says that the only reason Kovic is 
talking about challenging him is to sell more tickets to "Born on the Fourth of 
July," the film Kovic co-authored and which is now the country's No. 1 
box-office hit. 
</P>
<P>
"He's going to milk this thing for two months. This guy has no idea whatever of 
spending the next two years going back and forth to Washington, getting on and 
off airplanes. He's just out to hype the movie." 
</P>
<P>
Dornan mocks the Democrats' decision to recruit Kovic for the race against him. 
"They saw a wheelchair and said this guy's perfect for Dornan." 
</P>
<P>
He says the Democrats deserve an " 'F' for candidate research." He accuses them 
of finding the wrong man to run in the wrong district. 
</P>
<P>
On this, the peripatetic ex-Los Angeles talk-show host may have a point. Orange 
County is one of the most conservative areas in the country. Many of its 
middle-class voters honor the myth of an unbeatable, untarnished America, a 
nation that can do no wrong. 
</P>
<P>
What will Ron Kovic say to such people? How will a man who knows the crippling 
defeat and moral destructiveness of America's worst war campaign among her most 
ardent patriots? 
</P>
<P>
"I will talk about the building of a new American house," Kovic says without 
hesitation, "with a foundation that is based on truth, what we have gone 
through as a country and where we are going. I believe people have the strength 
of character to face up to this, to turn our wounds into wisdom. They are ready 
to be challenged again, just as they were by John F. Kennedy on that cold 
January day back in 1960." 
</P>
<P>
Does someone who speaks in such grand phrases know the hell he faces at the 
hands of Bob Dornan? 
</P>
<P>
"If I run, it will be an incredible battle, the most difficult challenge of my 
life." 
</P>
<P>
For a Marine sergeant who endured the horror of Vietnam and the inhumanity of a 
V.A. hospital and who has spent almost three decades in a wheelchair, this may 
indeed be an overstatement. Anyone who has been through what Kovic has can 
survive whatever brickbats "B-1 Bob" may throw at him. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Ron Kovic ; Photo, Robert Dornan Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
