<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA011490-0083 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 161881 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
January 14, 1990, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Part A; Page 9; Column 3; Foreign Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
81 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
WORLD IN BRIEF; 
</P>
<P>
SOUTH KOREA; 
</P>
<P>
FREE TRAVEL PROPOSAL REJECTED BY SEOUL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Communist North Korea proposed talks with South Korea on allowing free travel 
between the rival countries, but South Korea rejected the idea. The proposal 
was made in letters delivered in the border village of Panmunjom and addressed 
to South Korea's president, prime minister and three main opposition leaders. 
According to South Korean officials, North Korea repeated a proposal that the 
two Koreas hold "top-level political talks" to discuss free travel on the 
Korean peninsula. 
</P>
</TEXT>
