<HEADLINE>
<P>
DIGEST / LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF: TIP LEADS TO 44 ARRESTS AT SYLMAR COCKFIGHT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles police arrested 44 men and seized 50 gamecocks at a cockfight in 
Sylmar Saturday afternoon after receiving an anonymous phone tip, authorities 
said. 
</P>
<P>
The illegal fights were being staged in an arena in the back yard of a 
residence in the 12500 block of Bradley Avenue, said Sgt. Bill Thomas. 
</P>
<P>
The house's owner, Juan Duenas, 46, was cited for possession of fighting cocks, 
Sgt. Sol Polen said. 
</P>
<P>
Most of the men were given misdemeanor citations for being at a cockfight and 
released. 
</P>
<P>
The birds were taken to an animal shelter. 
</P>
<P>
If authorities identify the birds' owners, the owners can be charged with 
cruelty to animals, Thomas said. 
</P>
<P>
Police also confiscated scales used to weigh the birds before a match, and the 
razors that are attached to the birds' legs during the fight. 
</P>
<P>
One of the birds had injuries from a previous fight, Polen said. 
</P>
<P>
Authorities suspect that cockfighting, a sport imported from Mexico, occurs 
regularly in the primarily Latino areas of the northeast Valley, but officials 
say that raids are rare because the fights are usually clandestine and promoted 
only by word-of-mouth. 
</P>
<P>
The matches are usually between birds of equal weight. 
</P>
<P>
The birds' handlers, usually the owners, taunt the two birds by holding them 
beak-to-beak. 
</P>
<P>
Then the birds are dropped and the fight begins. A match usually lasts only a 
minute or so before one of the birds quits or is fatally slashed by the razors 
attached to the opponent's legs with electrical tape. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Brief; Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA011490-0152 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 162052 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
January 14, 1990, Sunday, Orange County Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Metro; Part B; Page 10; Column 1; Metro Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
398 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
COSTA MESA CAN SHOW IT REALLY HAS A HEART 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Costa Mesa City Council has an opportunity Monday to salvage the city's 
reputation as a community with a heart. It should rescind its decision to evict 
the Share Our Selves charity from a community center until a new location can 
be found. 
</P>
<P>
SOS plans to ask for a 2- to 3-month extension on its lease to give it time to 
negotiate purchase of a new site, an action made possible only last week by the 
generous outpouring of donations that have come in the wake of publicity over 
SOS's plight. The council majority, responding to neighborhood complaints about 
SOS, ordered the charity to move its food, clothing and financial assistance 
operations. Although the city offered to help SOS find another location, it 
balked when faced with the cost of helping it move to an industrial building 
the city had located. SOS's fate hung in the balance. 
</P>
<P>
But pressure has continued to build on the council, with Orange County 
religious leaders jumping into the fray. Summing up the matter, Father Michael 
P. Driscoll, the vicar of charities for the Diocese of Orange, said, "It 
strikes me that if Jesus lived today, the city of Costa Mesa would find him 
undesirable." Meanwhile, SOS supporters vowed to fast this weekend and Monday 
to try to get the council to reconsider its order to start eviction proceedings 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
On Friday, Mayor Peter F. Buffa made a new proposal to move SOS to Community 
Development Council offices in another part of town, well away from residential 
areas. Whether or not Buffa has the two votes needed to win approval of his 
plan is unclear at this time; it calls for the city to subsidize the lease by 
$177,658 over five years, with SOS paying slightly less. 
</P>
<P>
While that would be money well spent, the city should instead give SOS an 
extension on its current lease to give the charity the time needed to purchase 
its own building. This would not only relieve the city of financial 
responsibility but give SOS the autonomy it needs. The latter is important 
because there are City Council members who want to exclude illegal aliens from 
receiving SOS services, a restriction that cannot be tolerated. 
</P>
<P>
Two council members who voted against SOS in the past have accused the charity 
of dragging its feet and playing politics in order to get its way. Frankly, 
it's good to see SOS employing political pressure to save itself. We only hope 
it is not too late. 
</P>
</TEXT>
